  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1297475109" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1297475109" />
    <a title="Leo Walsh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2118933-leo-walsh"><img alt="Leo Walsh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442889406p2/2118933.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1297475109?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leo Walsh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leo Walsh" href="/user/show/2118933-leo-walsh">Leo Walsh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1297475109" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15627661304792645494">An interesting meditation of life, family and mortality -- but told by a garrulous 62-year-old guy drenched in whisky and smoking a Havana cigar reminiscing. And I enjoyed it. <br/><br/>It tells the unflinching story of two brothers from Cuba, Cesar and Nestor Castillo, who come to New York seeking their fame and fortune as mambo musicians. The brothers are young, poor and, like all young people, obsessed with sex and partying. It was amazing to watch the brothers grow as the novel progresses, especially </span>
  <span id="freeText15627661304792645494" style="display:none">An interesting meditation of life, family and mortality -- but told by a garrulous 62-year-old guy drenched in whisky and smoking a Havana cigar reminiscing. And I enjoyed it. <br /><br />It tells the unflinching story of two brothers from Cuba, Cesar and Nestor Castillo, who come to New York seeking their fame and fortune as mambo musicians. The brothers are young, poor and, like all young people, obsessed with sex and partying. It was amazing to watch the brothers grow as the novel progresses, especially the melancholic Nestor who moves from being a love-struck fool in rural Cuba to manhood in Havana to fatherhood in New York.<br /><br />Not that Nestor is perfect. He denies his intelligent wife Dolores the "right" to go to college. In the macho Cuban-American culture, this would shame Nestor. And yet, though he adheres to the ethic, he apologizes to her for having to deny her.<br /><br />That is a stroke of genius. As is having Dolores mope about Columbia's campus, drawn by the books, pretending to "fit in."<br /><br />Cesar, on the other hand, is more static. Instead of growing up and marrying, he continues living the life of a twenty-something well beyond his prime. Instead of confronting his mortality and lack of love head-on, he hides from reality in booze and empty sexual conquests -- which grow harder to pull off as he ages. <br /><br />Hijuelos' language is evocative, sensual and emotional. There were times I could not help thinking about Spanish-language soaps, which can pull off more melodrama in prime-time than our more sedate Anglo culture. Often to our detriment. <br /><br />All in all, a very enjoyable read. I thought the second half of the novel lagged with Cesar mourning his lost youth and demise. And while amusing at first, his preoccupation with his genitals got a bit old. But Cesar is Cesar. And Hijuelos' characterization quite believable. <br /><br />By the way, if you do get turned off by the middle bits, I invite you to stick around. Because the end includes Desi Arnaz, Lucille Ball, and perhaps the best bit of Magical Realism this side of Marquez. Which redeems the novel, saving it from the doldrums of the center. <br /><br />Highly recommended portrait of a group of immigrants in the 1950's. With a lot of sex and music.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15627661304792645494" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


