    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1692019763" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1692019763" />
    <a title="Pamela" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16275106-pamela"><img alt="Pamela" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1453469883p2/16275106.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1692019763?book_show_action=true">Mar 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pamela" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pamela" href="/user/show/16275106-pamela">Pamela</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780795337611" href="/book/show/19174454-the-mambo-kings-play-songs-of-love">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16275106-pamela?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16275106-pamela?shelf=pulitzer-fiction">pulitzer-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16275106-pamela?shelf=2019-pulitzer-reading-challenge">2019-pulitzer-reading-challenge</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1692019763" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15601581958552707987">The real strength of the Pulitzer Prize winning <b>The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love</b> lies in its language. So beautifully written that it is both mesmerizing and heartbreaking, it perfectly re-creates the world of Spanish Harlem in the late 1940s and 1950s. Two brothers, Cesar and Nestor Castillo make their way from Cuba to New York to begin a new life as musicians and eventually start a band called the Mambo Kings. <br/><br/>The story is told retrospectively mainly by Cesar when he is an old man drinking h</span>
  <span id="freeText15601581958552707987" style="display:none">The real strength of the Pulitzer Prize winning <b>The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love</b> lies in its language. So beautifully written that it is both mesmerizing and heartbreaking, it perfectly re-creates the world of Spanish Harlem in the late 1940s and 1950s. Two brothers, Cesar and Nestor Castillo make their way from Cuba to New York to begin a new life as musicians and eventually start a band called the Mambo Kings. <br /><br />The story is told retrospectively mainly by Cesar when he is an old man drinking himself to death in the Hotel Splendor. He sits and relives the life he and Nestor had both in Cuba and in America. The reader gets a contrasting picture of Nestor, shy and melancholy, who even while married to Delores still mourns his lost love Maria who left him long ago and Cesar, outgoing and determinedly macho who remembers every woman he ever had sex with, every plate of food or glass of beer he had. It is Cesar the book mainly deals with, his joy in life and his exuberance. All of this changes after Nestor dies and Cesar can't adjust to life without him. He begins to take on more of Nestor's melancholy nature.<br /><br /><b>Mambo Kings</b> has flaws. The plot is loosely structured and the novel could have used a good editing. Since most of it is based on endless description, it can be repetitive and long-winded, which editing would have tightened but the writing is so good that it can be difficult to decide what you would get rid of. Still, some of it repeats word for word several times. Then there's the matter of Cesar's penis. I'm not a prude and I get that the sexual descriptions served to underscore Cesar's machismo nature but, honestly, this thing should really have had a name. It got more character development and description than any of the female characters in the whole book. Loving descriptions of its size, its look, where it went and what it did rate as a third major character to me. Nevertheless, nothing can detract from the wonderful nature of this superbly written novel of life in all its color and sound. Say, take half a star off for the endless penis talk.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15601581958552707987" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


